Laredo Petroleum Chairman and CEO Randy Foutch speaks Wednesday at the Oklahoma Independent Petroleum Association’s wildcatters luncheon at Tulsa Country Club. Courtesy 








































































        
        CEO Randy Foutch talks Laredo Petroleum's strategy at 'Wildcatter' luncheon
    


By Casey Smith
Tulsa World


Nov 3, 2016
 0













































Laredo Petroleum Chairman and CEO Randy Foutch speaks Wednesday at the Oklahoma Independent Petroleum Association’s wildcatters luncheon at Tulsa Country Club. Courtesy





























































Chairman and CEO Randy Foutch has a handful of core tenets that have guided him and Laredo Petroleum’s senior management team in creating value for stakeholders of the Tulsa-based exploration and production company.One, he said, always hedge to protect anticipated cash flow.“We always try to hedge our product,” Foutch said. “We want to make sure that we can always pay debt and always make sure that we can pay salary. If you can pay debt and you can pay salary, you can always take hard knocks.”Foutch said Laredo typically tries to hedge in three-year contracts so that any short-term movement in oil prices doesn’t affect the company’s ability to perform. Current contracts mean that oil would have to be above $80 per barrel for the company to lose out, he said.Foutch made his remarks as part of “Wildcatter Wednesday,” a luncheon that the Oklahoma Independent Petroleum Association hosts to provide a forum for its membership to hear from oil and natural gas industry leaders as well as state and federal politicians. The monthly events alternate between Oklahoma City and Tulsa. Wednesday’s event was held at the Tulsa Country Club.OIPA is an advocacy group made up of more than 2,600 members working in exploration and production or affiliated businesses for the crude oil and and natural gas industries. The organization focuses on legislation, regulation and industry affairs.Laredo Petroleum’s focus is the Permian Basin. During the third quarter ending Sept. 30, Laredo produced a company record 51,276 barrels of oil equivalent per day and increased anticipated production growth for full-year 2016 to approximately 10 percent.During the same three-month period Laredo completed 10 horizontal development wells and reduced unit lease operating expenses to $3.85 per barrel of oil equivalent, down approximately 37 percent from the third-quarter 2015 rate of $6.09.Efficiency, Foutch said, requires long-term planning. In addition to hedging, Laredo’s plans for success consist of putting together a contiguous acreage position and having a plan to hold acreage by production; strong data collection and analysis; infrastructure investments; and maintaining liquidity and balance sheet flexibility.“We feel like data is critical — better data makes better decisions, and that’s been core to all of our companies,” Foutch said, referring to Laredo and the three companies that he previously founded and sold — Latigo Petroleum, Lariat Petroleum and Colt Resources.Foutch said that when Laredo Petroleum first went public in 2011, the company was criticized by some for putting so much money into data collection and on building infrastructure, but it is clear now that those decisions are paying off.Examples of both include Laredo’s multivariate Earth Model analysis of data that it has collected throughout eight years of development activity as well as the Medallion-Midland Basin pipeline system, a joint venture with Medallion Midstream LLC.


$3.95 a month: The new cost for doing business in Tulsa.
If you care about business and this community, it's a small price to pay to be in the know. For a limited time, get a digital subscription for just $3.95 a month. Sign up now at tulsaworld.com/subscribe.
Laredo owns a 49 percent interest in the pipeline that allows crude to be taken out of the Midland Basin and sold efficiently.During the second quarter of 2016, third-party volumes represented around 80 percent of total Medallion system volumes.“We get a fee for every barrel that goes through. It’s been a tremendous investment for us, and it’s worked out very well,” Foutch said.While responding to an audience member’s question about the future of crude oil prices, Foutch said there is always the possibility for world events to affect oil market prices. But for Laredo’s planning purposes they are forecasting that prices will be around $55 per barrel for the foreseeable future.“My view is that there’s probably some upside on prices, but I don’t see it reverting back to anything like it was,” Foutch said.























































Laredo Petroleum earnings
Laredo Petroleum announced its third-quarter earnings after the market closed Wednesday, reporting a net income of $9.5 million, or 4 cents per diluted share for the three-month period ending Sept. 30. Total revenue for the period was $159.7 million.The results show an improvement over the third quarter of 2015 when the company reported a loss of $847.8 million, a loss of $4.01 per diluted share, and total revenue of $150.3 million.





